Introduction ¶

Within the US, the reliance on the motor vehicle and its alignment with the classic "American Dream" has had undeniable ramifications on US cities and transportation infrastructure have been developed upon as well as the individuals that live within these cities. With this analysis, the intention is to dive deeper into the cost transportation has to an individual aswell as to the public at large using a handfull of algorithm's that we have been taught over the semester including decision trees to determine what states should be of target when providing a solution to the over saturation of personal motor vehicles within the US.

Cost to Individual ¶

Cost of Transportation Dependent on State ¶

Using the cost of living index from state to state we can determine how much of the average individuals salary goes towards transporation and from this determine the weight that transportation has on an individual from specific states helping us target what states could use an improvement to transportation costs.

Data Collection ¶

This dataset was pulled from 'World Population Review' in csv format. This dataset is a collection of weigted indexes that describe the cost of living within a state for the year of 2023. This dataset includes the living index, the grocery cost index, the housing cost index, the misc cost index, the transportation cost index, and the utility cost index. The average of each of these indexes, listed on the 'World Population Review', is equivalant to a 100 within the indexed dataset.

This dataset is an index dataset, meaning that it uses a baseline value that is to be compared to the full dataframe of index values. In my analysis I intend to convert these values from indexed to their proper dollar amounts.

  • The index value, where living is equivalent to 100 within the living column is equivalent to $61,334 otherwise known as the average cost of living within the state specified for a single year. (worldpopulationreview.com)

  • The ikndex value, where transportation is equivalent to 100 within the transportation column is equivalent to $9813.44 otherwise known as the average cost of transportation within the state specified for a single year. This is equivalent to 16% of the full living cost. (worldpopulationreview.com)

This implies that, on average, a United States citizen spends 16% of their yearly income exclusively on transportation. This value most likely changes from state to state dependent on the cost of living within that state and the infrastructure provided by the state in the area of living. Now I'm going to convert the index values to their monetary equivalents.

In [11]:
#COLM - Cost Of Living Monetarily
COLM = COLI.copy()

npLiv = COLI['living'].to_numpy()
npLivMon = ((npLiv / 100) * 61334)
COLM['living'] = npLivMon

npTranspo =  COLI['transportation'].to_numpy()
npTranspoMon = ((npTranspo / 100) * 9813.44)
COLM['transportation'] = npTranspoMon

COLM = COLM.round({'living':2, 'transportation': 2})

for k, v in COLI.iterrows():
    ax.annotate(v['state'], (v['livingToTransportation'],v['living']))

We can gather that there is a linear pattern, where as the living index declines, the cost of transportation increases. This implies that Transportation is a greater amount of the yearly income in lower living cost index states.

Data Manipulation ¶

Creating a Decision tree to decide what parameters states should have to be considered states of focus in improving the transportation index

In [17]:
# Initiation of Libraries
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.tree import export_graphviz
import pydot
In [18]:
lab = np.array(COLI['livingToTransportation'])

feat = COLI.drop(['state','livingToTransportation'], axis = 1)

feat_list = list(feat.columns)
feat = np.array(feat)
In [19]:
train_feat, test_feat, train_lab, test_lab = train_test_split(
    feat, lab, test_size = 0.25, random_state = 0)
In [20]:
# Instantiate model with 1000 decision trees
rf = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators = 1000, random_state = 0)

# Train the model on training data
rf.fit(train_feat, train_lab);
In [21]:
# Use the forest's predict method on the test data
predictions = rf.predict(test_feat)

# Calculate the absolute errors
errors = abs(predictions - test_lab)
print('Mean Absolute Error:', round(np.mean(errors), 2))

Mean Absolute Error: 0.36

Data Analysis ¶

With our decision tree we can conclude that out of the 28 states sampled for the tree, and out of all states, we will find that states with a lower living index are more in need of reformation to transportation. This pattern of behavior was recognized in the linear regression model from earlier solidifying the belief that lower living indexes require some reformation to transportation. Avenues of reformation will be explore further within our implementation section.

Implementation ¶

In order to improve transportation within the United States and reduce the transportation index within states of questions there are a few actions that can be taken. These include:

  • Promotion of Public Transportation
  • Invest in Active Transportation

Which will be expanded upon below

Promotion of Public Transportation ¶

Reducing the amount of vehicles would target the issue of over saturation signifigantly. A majority of households within the United States own at minimum one personal vehicle. Reducing the amount of vehicles on the roads and the cost of maitenance, gas, and insurance by reducing the number of vehicles is the objective. In order to do this we can promote the use of public transportation systems. It may be wise for the government to offer incentives to growing cities for public transportation systems. It also has personal benefits improving safety, health, and our focus, equity. (U.S. Department of Transportation)

Invest in Active Transportation ¶

Active Transportation is defined as transportation that does not require a personal motor vehicle, often by medium of walking, biking, scootering, or skating.(U.S. Department of Transportation) With a focus on infrastructure, cities can promote public transportation and focus on improving environments that focus on what people have available to them. Their own two feet. By using and creating more friendly walkable infrastructure that goes beyond the minimums a reduction of the personal motor vehicle is may be possible.

Adopt Electric Vehicles (EVs) ¶

For the individual electric vehicles can reduce the weight that fuel and maitenance plays on their own individual transportation index. By incentivizing the use of electric vehicles through the use of subsidies, tax credits, and charging station infrastructure we can reduce the weight the Personal Motor Vehicle has on the individuals transportation index.

Conclusion ¶

The American Reliance on the motor vehicle and it's implications its had on its people is evident by the amount of money specifically used for transportation needs within the United States. Through the use of indexed data on living transportation, linear regression, and decision trees within this analysis it could be gathered what specific states could be of target for transportation reformation. The three Implementations are just a few of the many implementations that could be explored. In the future it may be of interest to look further into the avenues of reformation and looking into the expansion of Public Transportation, Active Transportation, and Electric Vehicles.
